==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*þurnu-'', from Indo-European ''*(s)tern-'', a variant of the base ''*(s)ter-, *(s)terə-'' ‘rigid, stiff’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[thorn]] (Dutch [[doorn]]), Old High German [[thorn]] (German [[Dorn]]), Old Norse ''þorn'' (Swedish [[torn]]), Gothic [[𐌸𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌽𐌿𐍃]].  The Indo-European root is also the source of Old Church Slavonic [[трьнъ]] (Russian [[тёрн]] ‘sloe, blackthorn’), Sanskrit [[तृण]] ‘grass’.

